  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How did you get into IIM?",
  "response": "Getting into the Indian Institutes of Management (IIMs) typically involves a multi-step process that centers around the Common Admission Test (CAT), along with other criteria. Here\u2019s a general outline of the steps one might take to gain admission:\n\n1. **Educational Background**: Most candidates have a bachelor's degree from a recognized university. While there is no specific requirement for the field of study, having a strong academic record can be beneficial.\n\n2. **Preparing for the CAT**: The CAT is a competitive entrance exam that tests quantitative ability, verbal ability, data interpretation, and logical reasoning. Candidates usually spend months preparing for it through self-study, coaching classes, or study groups.\n\n3. **Taking the CAT**: Candidates register for and take the CAT, usually held once a year. The exam consists of multiple-choice questions and non-MCQ questions.\n\n4. **Securing a Good Percentile**: After the exam, candidates receive a percentile score. A high percentile is crucial for qualifying for the next stages of the admissions process. Each IIM has a different cutoff percentile.\n\n5. **Shortlisting for Further Rounds**: Based on CAT scores, IIMs shortlist candidates for further selection rounds, which may include Group Discussions (GD), Personal Interviews (PI), and Written Ability Tests (WAT).\n\n6. **Performance in Selection Rounds**: Candidates must perform well in the GD/PI/WAT, where their communication skills, personality, leadership qualities, and overall fit for the program are assessed.\n\n7. **Final Selection**: After all the rounds are completed, the IIMs compile scores based on CAT scores, performance in the selection rounds, and sometimes past academic performance and work experience. A final merit list is prepared for admission offers.\n\n8. **Liaising for Admission**: Once selected, candidates will receive an offer and need to complete the admission formalities, including payment of fees and enrollment.\n\nEach IIM may have slightly different criteria and processes, but this general framework applies broadly across the prestigious institution.",
